<HEAD>MCorp Sells Bank in Corpus Christi</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   MCorp will sell its interest in MBank <LOCATION>Corpus
Christi</LOCATION> to the bank's managers, company officials said <DATE>Friday</DATE>. It
would be the second such transaction in less than two weeks.
   The deal, which is subject to regulatory and bankruptcy court
approvals, would leave <ORGANIZATION>MCorp</ORGANIZATION>, once the state's second-largest bank
holding company, with three subsidiaries to sell.
   A group of investors led by <PERSON>Jerry Gates</PERSON>, chairman and chief
executive officer of <ORGANIZATION>MBank Corpus Christi</ORGANIZATION>, will become the bank's
owner under an agreement with <ORGANIZATION>MCorp</ORGANIZATION>. The sale is expected to be
complete by <DATE>July 31</DATE>.
   The bank had assets of <MONEY>$582 million</MONEY> and deposits of <MONEY>$502 million</MONEY>
on <DATE>Dec. 31, 1989</DATE>.
   The bank's name will be changed to <ORGANIZATION>Corpus Christi National Bank</ORGANIZATION>,
the name under which it was originally chartered 100 years ago.
   ``Over the past few months, as events unfolded which made it
appear that local ownership of the bank was a possibility, we've
received hundreds of comments from customers and community leaders
expressing their support for the return of <ORGANIZATION>Corpus Christi National
Bank</ORGANIZATION>,'' <PERSON>Gates</PERSON> said.
   Terms of the agreement call for <ORGANIZATION>MCorp</ORGANIZATION> to receive an undisclosed
amount of assets, mostly loans and real estate, for the bank's
stock. MBank <ORGANIZATION>Corpus Christi</ORGANIZATION> will simultaneously issue <MONEY>$20 million</MONEY>
in new stock.
   MCorp, which has been in bankruptcy proceedings since <DATE>March
1989</DATE>, last week said it had reached an agreement to sell <ORGANIZATION>MBank El
Paso</ORGANIZATION> to its managers.
   The Dallas-based firm is trying to sell its remaining banking
subsidiaries in <LOCATION>Brownsville</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>New Braunfels</LOCATION> and Waco.
   ``We are looking to sell those assuming we can get what we view
as adequate or proper value for the benefit of our shareholders,''
said <ORGANIZATION>MCorp</ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON>Doug Hughes</PERSON>.
   The five banks remained with <ORGANIZATION>MCorp</ORGANIZATION> after the <ORGANIZATION>Federal Deposit
Insurance Corp.</ORGANIZATION> stripped it of 20 banking subsidiaries following
the bankruptcy filing. Those 20 banks were bought by <ORGANIZATION>Banc One
Corp.</ORGANIZATION>, an <LOCATION>Ohio</LOCATION> banking company, and now operate as <ORGANIZATION>Bank One-Texas</ORGANIZATION>.
   MCorp's federally assisted bailout was the third largest in
history after those of <ORGANIZATION>Continental Illinois</ORGANIZATION> in <DATE>1984</DATE> and <ORGANIZATION>First
Republic Corp.</ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION>Dallas</LOCATION> in <DATE>1988</DATE>.
</TEXT>
