<HEAD>Court Will Study Appeal of Convicted Chicago Murderer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   <ORGANIZATION>The Supreme Court</ORGANIZATION> today agreed to study the
appeal of a convicted <LOCATION>Chicago</LOCATION> murderer sentenced to 50 to 100 years
in prison for his crime.
   The justices said they will use <PERSON>Warren Lee Harris</PERSON>' case to give
federal courts some further guidance in how to handle the appeals
of defendants convicted in state courts.
   <PERSON>Harris</PERSON> was convicted of the <DATE>July 19, 1977</DATE>, murder in <LOCATION>Chicago</LOCATION> of
<LOCATION>Earnest Howard</LOCATION>.
   After his conviction was upheld by the <LOCATION>Illinois</LOCATION> courts on direct
appeal, <PERSON>Harris</PERSON> filed a so-called habeas corpus appeal in state
courts. In it, he contended for the first time that he was denied
adequate legal help at his trial.
   State courts ruled that <PERSON>Harris</PERSON> could not raise that issue
because he had failed to raise it on direct appeal, but it then
rejected the merits of <PERSON>Harris</PERSON>' ineffective-assistance argument.
   Harris then sought help from the federal courts, in a habeas
corpus petition raising the same issue.
   A federal trial judge ruled that <PERSON>Harris</PERSON>' procedural default,
which usually would preclude federal court review of his claim, had
been waived by the state courts.
   But the <ORGANIZATION>7th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals</ORGANIZATION> <DATE>last June 12</DATE> ruled
that the procedural default blocks federal court review of the
ineffective-assistance argument.
   The case is <ORGANIZATION>Harris vs. Reed</ORGANIZATION>, 87-5677.
</TEXT>
