FT  12 NOV 92 / Court asked to end Osman case
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
COUNSEL for <PERSON>Mr Kenneth Clarke</PERSON>, the home secretary, has asked the High Court
to end the five-year legal battle of <PERSON>Mr Lorrain Osman</PERSON> to avoid extradition
to <LOCATION>Hong Kong</LOCATION>.
<PERSON>Mr Osman</PERSON>, 60, <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION>'s longest-serving unconvicted prisoner, faces theft
and fraud charges. He is making his ninth application for a writ of habeas
corpus, freeing him from custody at <LOCATION>Brixton</LOCATION> prison in <LOCATION>south London</LOCATION>.
<PERSON>Mr Stephen Richards</PERSON>, for the home secretary, said <PERSON>Mr Osman</PERSON>'s attempt to
avoid his removal by repeatedly applying for writs of habeas corpus and
judicial review should now end.
He said the court should allow extradition to go ahead, even if <PERSON>Mr Osman</PERSON>
launched a 10th application for a writ. Judgment was reserved.
</TEXT>
