<HEAD>American in Solitary Confinement, Lawyer Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SANTOSH BASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CALCUTTA, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An American member of a mysterious Hindu
cult has been held in virtual solitary confinement since her
detainment last month by the Communist-governed <LOCATION>West Bengal</LOCATION> state,
her lawyer said <DATE>Tuesday</DATE>.
   <PERSON>Patricia Munday</PERSON>, 38, of <LOCATION>Vermont</LOCATION>, is not receiving the necessary
medical treatment, according to a petition filed in <LOCATION>West Bengal</LOCATION>
Court by her attorney, <PERSON>Bholanath Sen.</PERSON> Her hometown was not
immediately known.
   ``<LOCATION>West Bengal</LOCATION> government does not believe in individual
liberty,'' the lawyer said.
   Munday was detained by the <LOCATION>West Bengal</LOCATION> police <DATE>Jan. 27</DATE>,
apparently for her links with a cult called the <ORGANIZATION>Anand Marg</ORGANIZATION>, or the
<ORGANIZATION>Path of Bliss</ORGANIZATION>. The governing Communist coalition is opposed to the
cult.
   Munday is being held in a private hospital in <LOCATION>Calcutta</LOCATION>, the
capital. She is guarded by police and journalists are not allowed
to see her. The petition asks that she be moved to a hospital in
<LOCATION>New Delhi</LOCATION>.
   The habeas corpus petition was filed after the <ORGANIZATION>Indian Supreme
Court</ORGANIZATION> on <DATE>Friday</DATE> ordered the government not to deport her. She had
appealed to the <ORGANIZATION>Supreme Court</ORGANIZATION> to secure her release.
   Habeas corpus requires a person in custody be brought before a
court. It places the burden of proof on those detaining the person
to justify the action.
   ``<PERSON>Ms. Munday</PERSON> has been kept in virtual solitary confinement. ...
She needs better medical treatment, her injuries are yet to heal,''
<PERSON>Sen</PERSON> said.
   <LOCATION>West Bengal</LOCATION>'s advocate general, <PERSON>Naranarayan Goopu</PERSON>, said there
was no need for the court to act on the petition because a similar
writ is pending before the <ORGANIZATION>Supreme Court</ORGANIZATION> and will be heard <DATE>Friday</DATE>.
   Gooptu denied <PERSON>Munday</PERSON> is being held in solitary confinement,
telling the court that police ``have only restricted her movement.''
   <PERSON>Munday</PERSON>, a member of the <ORGANIZATION>United Nations</ORGANIZATION> team that won the <DATE>1981</DATE>
Nobel peace prize for its work with refugees in <LOCATION>Somalia</LOCATION>, arrived in
<LOCATION>India</LOCATION> from <LOCATION>Katmandu</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Nepal</LOCATION>, on a private visit. A mob attacked her
and an associate on <DATE>Jan. 26</DATE> when they were traveling on a
motorcycle near the <ORGANIZATION>Anand Marg</ORGANIZATION> headquarters in <LOCATION>West Bengal</LOCATION>'s
<LOCATION>Purulia</LOCATION> district.
   Munday suffered head injuries. The <LOCATION>Purulia</LOCATION> police, instead of
lodging her complaint, detained her the next day. She later was
moved to the hospital in <LOCATION>Calcutta</LOCATION>.
   The <ORGANIZATION>Anand Marg</ORGANIZATION> says it aims to create a social, economic and
spiritual order that will replace both capitalism and communism. It
claims to have branches worldwide.
</TEXT>
