<TEXT>
   <ORGANIZATION>Southwest Airlines</ORGANIZATION> said it plans to expand the sale of airline tickets through automated teller machines in 7-Eleven stores to four <LOCATION>Texas</LOCATION> cities. 

   Tickets will be available from <DATE>today</DATE> until <DATE>May 31</DATE> through about 500 automated teller machines in <LOCATION>Houston</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Dallas</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>San Antonio</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Corpus Christi</LOCATION>, according to <ORGANIZATION>TransFirst Corp.</ORGANIZATION>, the operator of the MoneyMaker automated teller network. 

   The airline said it will reevaluate the program after <DATE>May 31</DATE>. 
If it proves successful in the new markets, <ORGANIZATION>Southwest</ORGANIZATION> probably will expand the program to additional cities. 

   <ORGANIZATION>Southwest</ORGANIZATION> said it decided to expand the program because of a successful test in <LOCATION>Corpus Christi</LOCATION>. 
As previously reported, <ORGANIZATION>Southwest</ORGANIZATION> began testing the concept last <DATE>October</DATE>. 

   Only one type of ticket -- a <MONEY>$15</MONEY> standby fare for passengers between the ages of 18 and 21 -- will be available through the automated teller machines. 
The fare will be good for flights between <LOCATION>Houston</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Dallas</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>San Antonio</LOCATION> and for flights between <LOCATION>Houston</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Corpus Christi</LOCATION>. 

</TEXT>
