<HEAD>Three Missing in Gulf Crash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CORPUS CHRISTI, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three people were missing from a
private, single-engine plane that crashed into the <LOCATION>Gulf of Mexico</LOCATION>
<DATE>Wednesday</DATE> <TIME>night</TIME>, <ORGANIZATION>Coast Guard</ORGANIZATION> officials said.
   The <ORGANIZATION>Cessna</ORGANIZATION> 210 with four people aboard went down about 30 miles
south of Palacios at <TIME>8:27 p.m.</TIME> while en route from <LOCATION>Brownsville</LOCATION> to
<LOCATION>Houston</LOCATION>, said Petty Officer <PERSON>Steve Guy</PERSON> at <ORGANIZATION>Coast Guard</ORGANIZATION> district
headquarters in <LOCATION>New Orleans</LOCATION>.
   A man who was in the plane swam to a nearby oil platform and was
talking by cellular telephone to a <ORGANIZATION>Coast Guard</ORGANIZATION> duty officer in
<LOCATION>Galveston</LOCATION>, said Petty Officer <PERSON>Clifton Vigus</PERSON> in <LOCATION>Corpus Christi</LOCATION>. The
<ORGANIZATION>Coast Guard</ORGANIZATION> was trying to pinpoint the location of the platform and
rescue craft had been dispatched.
   The other three people were unaccounted for, <PERSON>Vigus</PERSON> said.
   Palacios is a coastal community about halfway between <LOCATION>Corpus
Christi</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Galveston</LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
