<HEAD>Supreme Court Sidesteps Jury Issue in Illinois Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The <ORGANIZATION>Supreme Court</ORGANIZATION> today sidestepped deciding
whether a criminal defendant's right to be tried by his peers is
violated when prosecutors disqualify potential jurors based on their
race.
   By a 7-2 vote, the justices ruled against <PERSON>Frank D. Teague</PERSON>,
sentenced to 30 years in prison for the armed robbery of a <LOCATION>Chicago</LOCATION>
supermarket and for the attempted murder of police officers shot
after the robbery.
   Four justices _ one vote short of the majority needed to set
binding legal precedent _ said <PERSON>Teague</PERSON> should not be allowed to raise
the representative-jury issue.
   The four, led by <ORGANIZATION>Justice Sandra Day O'Connor</ORGANIZATION>, said federal courts
should not establish new constitutional guidelines when ruling on
so-called habeas corpus appeals by criminal defendants.
   Such appeals attack a defendant's state court conviction or
sentence on grounds that federal constitutional rights were
violated. The appeals always follow unsuccessful state court appeals
by the defendants.
   The justices in <DATE>1986</DATE> ruled that prosecutors never may disqualify
potential jurors based on their race. The court said such tactics
violate equal-protection rights.
   But a subsequent decision strictly limited the retroactive effect
of the <DATE>1986</DATE> ruling. The court said previously that the <DATE>1986</DATE> ruling
does not apply to convicted criminals who, like <PERSON>Teague</PERSON>, had
exhausted direct appeals in state courts prior to when the <DATE>1986</DATE>
ruling was announced.
   Teague's habeas corpus appeal did not raise the equal-protection
issue, but instead attacked a prosecutor's exclusion of 10 potential
black jurors on grounds that it violated <PERSON>Teague</PERSON>'s right to a jury
selected from a cross-section of the community.
   <PERSON>Teague</PERSON>, who is black, was convicted in <DATE>1978</DATE> by an all-white jury.
   If <PERSON>Teague</PERSON> were to win on the fair cross-section challenge, he
would be entitled to a new trial even though the high court's <DATE>1986</DATE>
ruling came too late to help him.
   <ORGANIZATION>Past Supreme Court</ORGANIZATION> rulings have applied the Sixth Amendment's
fair cross-section requirement to pools of potential jurors but not
to juries actually selected.
   <PERSON>O'Connor</PERSON> said the court should not decide whether the fair
cross-section requirement applies to selected juries as well because
that ruling could not apply to <PERSON>Teague</PERSON>.
   Her opinion was joined by Chief Justice <PERSON>William H. Rehnquist</PERSON> and
Justices <PERSON>Antonin Scalia</PERSON> and <PERSON>Anthony M. Kennedy</PERSON>.
   Justices <PERSON>Byron R. White</PERSON>, <PERSON>Harry A. Blackmun</PERSON> and <PERSON>John Paul Stevens</PERSON>
also voted to uphold <PERSON>Teague</PERSON>'s conviction but for differing reasons.
   Justices <PERSON>William J. Brennan</PERSON> and <PERSON>Thurgood Marshall</PERSON> dissented.
   The case is <PERSON>Teague vs. Lane</PERSON>, 87-5259.
</TEXT>
